  "prompt": "Can you hard boil eggs in the microwave?",
  "response": "Yes, you can hard-boil eggs in the microwave, but it requires care and the right technique to avoid accidents like eggs exploding. Here\u2019s a safe method to hard-boil eggs in the microwave:\n\n---\n\n### **Method: Using a Microwave-Safe Bowl**\n1. **Prepare the eggs**: Place the eggs in a microwave-safe bowl. Do not microwave eggs in their shells directly, as they can explode.\n2. **Add water**: Fill the bowl with enough lukewarm water to completely cover the eggs.\n3. **Add salt**: Add a pinch of salt to the water. This helps prevent the eggs from exploding.\n4. **Microwave**: Cover the bowl with a microwave-safe plate or lid. Microwave on medium power (50-70%) for about 6-8 minutes, depending on your microwave's wattage.\n5. **Check for doneness**: Carefully remove the bowl (it will be hot) and check if the eggs are done. If not, microwave in short 1-minute bursts.\n6. **Cool the eggs**: Once cooked, transfer the eggs to a bowl of cold water or an ice bath to stop the cooking process and make them easier to peel.\n\n---\n\n### **Alternative Method: Using an Egg Cooker**\nSome microwave-safe egg cookers are specifically designed for boiling or poaching eggs. Follow the instructions on the cooker for best results.\n\n---\n\n### **Important Safety Tips**:\n- **Never microwave eggs in their shells directly**. This can cause them to explode due to steam buildup.\n- **Use a microwave-safe container** and cover it to prevent splatters.\n- **Be cautious when handling** the bowl or eggs, as they will be very hot.\n\nIf you\u2019re unsure, using a stovetop to hard-boil eggs is a safer and more traditional method.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
